WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:03.100
You know, it's actually kind of funny how we talk about the economy.

00:03.540 --> 00:03.980
How do you mean?

00:04.360 --> 00:09.580
Well, if you really listen to the language we use, there's this underlying assumption

00:09.580 --> 00:13.740
that it operates almost exactly like the weather.

00:14.300 --> 00:17.320
Oh, right. Yeah, like it's a force of nature.

00:17.480 --> 00:24.000
Exactly. It's treated as this massive chaotic system of natural uncontrollable forces.

00:24.400 --> 00:29.560
You check the morning news over your coffee and you see the headlines, right?

00:30.000 --> 00:34.980
Interest rates are up. Inflation is down. The job market is cooling off.

00:35.120 --> 00:38.180
Yeah, even cooling off, it's a thermodynamic term.

00:38.300 --> 00:45.660
Right. And we're taught to react to those updates the exact same way we react to a forecast of a thunderstorm.

00:46.100 --> 00:48.900
You grab an umbrella. You tighten your belt.

00:49.100 --> 00:49.860
You just adapt.

00:50.220 --> 00:54.440
You accept that these are just the natural laws of the free market playing out

00:54.440 --> 00:59.160
and your only real option is to just, well, deal with it.

00:59.160 --> 01:03.480
It's so pervasive, isn't it? That whole framing of inevitability.

01:03.480 --> 01:09.060
We constantly hear phrases like market forces or economic gravity.

01:09.400 --> 01:10.700
The natural rate of unemployment.

01:11.280 --> 01:12.200
Yes, exactly.

01:13.140 --> 01:20.800
That implies a system governed by neutral, unfeeling physics that sits entirely outside of human control.

01:20.800 --> 01:24.940
The narrative is that nobody's really pulling the levers.

01:25.080 --> 01:26.560
The machine just runs.

01:26.900 --> 01:31.600
But I think a lot of people, and honestly, if you're listening to this, you might be one of them,

01:32.000 --> 01:35.380
have had this sneaking suspicion at some point.

01:35.760 --> 01:38.120
A suspicion that maybe it's not nature.

01:38.120 --> 01:43.160
Yeah, this feeling that maybe the economy isn't a force of nature at all.

01:43.540 --> 01:49.420
This suspicion that it's actually a game, but a game where the rules are completely invisible.

01:49.640 --> 01:52.060
Invisible, but rigidly enforced.

01:52.340 --> 01:57.440
Right. And enforced in a way that makes you feel like you were deliberately set up to lose.

01:57.960 --> 01:59.780
Well, what if that isn't just a feeling?

02:00.180 --> 02:05.220
What if we could actually map the literal mathematical geometry of those rules?

02:05.220 --> 02:06.800
It's a fascinating premise.

02:07.080 --> 02:08.420
Welcome to this deep dive.

02:08.800 --> 02:11.780
If you're joining us today, you, the listener, need to settle in,

02:11.820 --> 02:18.320
because we are in for an incredibly dense, fascinating, and really timely exploration today.

02:18.520 --> 02:19.480
We definitely are.

02:19.540 --> 02:21.000
We have a very specific mission.

02:21.140 --> 02:26.400
We are taking a 2026 academic paper by the independent researcher Flyxion.

02:26.700 --> 02:29.340
It's titled The Entropy of Austerity.

02:29.560 --> 02:30.760
Such a great title.

02:31.000 --> 02:31.800
It really is.

02:31.800 --> 02:36.780
And our goal is to take its incredibly heavy physics and computational math

02:36.780 --> 02:43.600
and translate it into a highly accessible, mind-bending new way to look at how the world works.

02:44.900 --> 02:46.560
Okay, let's unpack this.

02:46.780 --> 02:48.540
What exactly are we dealing with here?

02:48.760 --> 02:50.940
Well, it really is a remarkable piece of synthesis.

02:51.360 --> 02:58.540
What Flyxion has done is take the deeply historical and economic work of Clara E. Mattei.

02:58.540 --> 03:01.960
Specifically her 2022 book, The Capital Order, right?

03:02.140 --> 03:06.740
Yes, and her brand new 2026 release, Escape from Capitalism.

03:07.240 --> 03:13.680
So Flyxion takes that history and feeds it into two highly complex scientific frameworks.

03:13.800 --> 03:14.200
Which are?

03:14.360 --> 03:17.260
The first is something called the RSVP model.

03:17.520 --> 03:20.800
That stands for Relativistic Scalar Vector Plenum.

03:21.260 --> 03:21.620
Wow.

03:21.620 --> 03:22.940
I know, it's a mouthful.

03:23.320 --> 03:29.220
And the second is Sphere Pop Dynamics, which deals with the architecture of irreversible computation.

03:29.520 --> 03:36.360
Okay, I have to admit, when I first saw those terms, you know, Relativistic Scalar Vector Plenum and irreversible computation,

03:36.860 --> 03:40.900
my immediate thought was that we were about to reverse engineer a warp drive.

03:41.240 --> 03:42.440
It definitely sounds like it.

03:42.440 --> 03:48.340
It sounds super intimidating, but I promise you, as we work our way through this deep dive,

03:48.800 --> 03:53.420
you are going to see how these exact concepts explain the numbers on your paycheck,

03:54.020 --> 03:57.900
the cost of your groceries, and the headlines on your news feed.

03:58.000 --> 03:59.960
It maps perfectly onto reality.

04:00.140 --> 04:00.900
It really does.

04:01.400 --> 04:03.260
But before we jump into the deep end,

04:03.680 --> 04:08.100
we do need to lay down a very clear objective disclaimer for everyone listening.

04:08.180 --> 04:09.560
Yes, that's crucial.

04:09.560 --> 04:16.160
The source material we are covering today, both Maddy's historical analysis and Flyxion's mathematical mapping of it,

04:16.800 --> 04:19.820
it contains highly politically charged critiques.

04:20.000 --> 04:25.440
Very pointed critiques of capitalism, of austerity measures, and class dynamics.

04:25.580 --> 04:25.780
Right.

04:26.020 --> 04:27.800
And here's the crucial point for you.

04:28.420 --> 04:31.880
We are absolutely not taking a political side here.

04:31.880 --> 04:40.220
We aren't endorsing these views, nor are we making any judgment on right-wing versus left-wing economics.

04:40.280 --> 04:42.440
That is completely outside our job description.

04:42.560 --> 04:43.080
Exactly.

04:43.440 --> 04:49.480
Our goal today is strictly to explore the intellectual exercise that the author of this paper has performed.

04:50.240 --> 04:57.880
Taking social and economic policies and mapping them onto fluid dynamics and theoretical physics is just...

04:58.440 --> 05:01.260
It's a brilliant structural experiment.

05:01.260 --> 05:04.220
Regardless of where you fall on the political spectrum.

05:04.460 --> 05:04.940
Exactly.

05:05.420 --> 05:09.980
We are here to impartially report on the content provided, nothing more.

05:10.260 --> 05:13.020
It functions as a phenomenal thought experiment.

05:13.640 --> 05:16.820
Whether you agree with the underlying political premises or not,

05:16.980 --> 05:24.740
asking what does a macroeconomic policy actually look like if we map it as a mathematical topography.

05:24.740 --> 05:30.360
It's just a powerful way to pressure test our baseline assumptions.

05:31.020 --> 05:35.960
Okay, so to begin unpacking this, we really can't start with the math, can we?

05:36.100 --> 05:38.300
No, the math won't make sense without the history.

05:38.520 --> 05:38.780
Right.

05:38.960 --> 05:44.200
We have to start where the paper starts, which is the historical groundwork laid out by Clara Mante.

05:44.880 --> 05:52.020
Because to understand how the physics work, we first have to understand the post-World War I crisis of capitalism.

05:52.020 --> 05:58.540
The immediate aftermath of the First World War really is the crucible for modern economic policy.

05:58.700 --> 06:07.040
According to her research, everything we understand about modern austerity, the budget cuts, the interest rate hikes we debate today,

06:07.220 --> 06:10.520
it all starts in that specific historical window.

06:10.520 --> 06:15.200
Yeah, to set the scene properly, we have to look at the mindset before the war.

06:16.260 --> 06:22.880
Before WWI, the private ownership of production, the gold standard, the mechanics of the free market,

06:23.440 --> 06:29.300
these were largely accepted by the general public as just the natural order of the universe.

06:29.620 --> 06:31.320
It was the water everyone swam in.

06:31.320 --> 06:31.800
Exactly.

06:31.980 --> 06:37.500
There wasn't a widespread mainstream questioning of whether the factory owner should own the factory.

06:37.700 --> 06:38.520
It just was.

06:38.520 --> 06:45.340
But during the war, something completely unprecedented happened across Europe.

06:45.620 --> 06:46.660
Because of the war effort, right?

06:46.860 --> 06:53.860
Out of sheer existential necessity to sustain the war effort, governments essentially suspended the free market.

06:54.040 --> 06:55.980
Wait, they just paused capitalism?

06:56.320 --> 06:57.320
Effectively, yes.

06:57.580 --> 07:00.120
They took over massive sectors of the economy.

07:00.120 --> 07:09.540
We are talking about the direct state management of coal mines, of railway networks, shipping, food production, distribution.

07:09.900 --> 07:11.760
Because they couldn't afford the inefficiency.

07:12.020 --> 07:13.720
It was wartime collectivization.

07:13.940 --> 07:14.500
Precisely.

07:14.980 --> 07:17.660
The government stepped in and effectively said,

07:18.220 --> 07:25.100
we cannot rely on the chaotic, profit-driven free market to ensure we have enough coal and steel to fight this war.

07:25.300 --> 07:27.760
We have to centrally organize it ourselves.

07:28.280 --> 07:29.320
To ensure survival.

07:29.320 --> 07:29.820
Right.

07:30.000 --> 07:34.720
And they proved that alternative systems of mass organization could function.

07:35.820 --> 07:40.940
And this had an unintended but profound psychological effect on the working class.

07:41.720 --> 07:42.300
I bet.

07:42.980 --> 07:51.300
They look at this massive wartime command economy and realize something highly dangerous to the established order.

07:51.420 --> 07:52.460
Which was?

07:52.460 --> 08:00.120
That private ownership of the means of production was not a natural, inescapable law of nature.

08:00.740 --> 08:02.120
It was a political choice.

08:02.120 --> 08:04.580
The logic was totally clear to them.

08:04.960 --> 08:09.200
If the government could organize the railways and the factories to fight a brutal war,

08:09.440 --> 08:15.020
why couldn't the workers organize those same railways and factories to benefit society and peacetime?

08:15.020 --> 08:18.280
The illusion of inevitability was completely shattered.

08:18.520 --> 08:18.840
Yes.

08:19.440 --> 08:26.000
The paper calls this a moment where the perceived naturalness of capitalism fractured.

08:26.000 --> 08:29.220
And it wasn't just like a philosophical awakening.

08:29.220 --> 08:33.220
It led to massive, tangible movements on the ground.

08:33.360 --> 08:34.860
People weren't just writing pamphlets.

08:34.980 --> 08:36.400
They were taking action.

08:36.780 --> 08:38.820
You had Lord di nuovo in Italy.

08:39.080 --> 08:39.260
Right.

08:39.340 --> 08:40.820
Which wasn't just a political party.

08:41.180 --> 08:47.880
It was a movement of workers actively taking over factories in Turin and running them via worker councils.

08:47.880 --> 08:57.440
And you had shop steward councils in Britain effectively bypassing traditional union leadership to control the shop floors directly.

08:57.740 --> 09:07.200
They were literally showing, in real time, alternative ways to organize society and production without the traditional owners.

09:07.400 --> 09:11.600
It was what Mattei identifies as a true crisis of the capital order.

09:11.720 --> 09:11.900
Right.

09:12.160 --> 09:16.220
And you have to put yourself in the shoes of the establishment at that moment.

09:16.220 --> 09:20.920
The people who own the factories, the major creditors, the political elite.

09:21.060 --> 09:22.120
They must have been terrified.

09:22.400 --> 09:23.660
They were absolutely terrified.

09:23.860 --> 09:29.540
The working class was realizing they didn't necessarily need the owners to make society function.

09:30.300 --> 09:35.240
So, according to Mattei's historical analysis, they fought back.

09:36.100 --> 09:45.420
A coalition of technocrats, economists, and political leaders, primarily in Britain and Italy, at first systematically invented a counteroffensive.

09:45.420 --> 09:50.060
They recognized that they needed to restore the conditions of market dependence.

09:50.700 --> 09:57.040
They needed to make the working class dependent on wage labor again to force them back into the traditional hierarchy.

09:57.440 --> 10:04.640
And their weapon of choice, the tool they designed to accomplish this, is what Mattei terms the austerity trinity.

10:05.040 --> 10:06.780
The austerity trinity.

10:06.780 --> 10:13.760
Let's break that down piece by piece, because these are terms you still hear on the news literally every week today.

10:13.960 --> 10:16.400
Fiscal, monetary, and industrial.

10:16.760 --> 10:21.840
Let's start with fiscal austerity, as that's the one most people are familiar with.

10:22.480 --> 10:27.540
This is what we typically think of when a politician talks about tightening our belts.

10:27.900 --> 10:28.840
Cutting public standing.

10:28.840 --> 10:34.360
Slashing budgets for health, education, housing, and welfare.

10:34.640 --> 10:39.200
It's the aggressive rolling back of the state's provision of social goods.

10:39.400 --> 10:39.600
Right.

10:39.940 --> 10:42.860
And then the second pillar is monetary austerity.

10:43.100 --> 10:43.500
Mm-hmm.

10:43.780 --> 10:48.820
Which feels a bit more abstract to the average person, but hits just as hard.

10:49.100 --> 10:49.660
It does.

10:50.380 --> 10:56.940
Monetary austerity involves central banks intervening to raise interest rates and contract the money supply.

10:56.940 --> 10:58.660
So it makes money harder to borrow.

10:59.140 --> 11:00.420
It makes money harder to borrow.

11:00.900 --> 11:03.060
It increases the cost of existing debt.

11:03.600 --> 11:07.140
And it intentionally slows down economic activity.

11:07.880 --> 11:08.580
And the third pillar?

11:08.920 --> 11:10.400
Industrial austerity.

11:10.860 --> 11:19.420
This is the direct, often aggressive suppression of wages, the dismantling of labor unions, and the rolling back of worker protections.

11:20.080 --> 11:23.560
It's the effort to make labor cheaper and more pliable.

11:23.560 --> 11:31.840
Now, normally, when politicians talk about austerity today, they use the language of a household budget.

11:31.920 --> 11:33.320
We've maxed out the credit card.

11:33.600 --> 11:33.760
Yeah.

11:33.920 --> 11:36.400
They say, look, we've been spending too much.

11:36.500 --> 11:37.880
We need to balance the books.

11:38.160 --> 11:42.480
We need to eat our vegetables now so the economy can heal and grow later.

11:42.680 --> 11:44.300
That's the standard line.

11:44.300 --> 11:50.880
But, if I'm understanding the paper correctly, the historical context completely flips that narrative.

11:51.280 --> 11:56.440
In this framing, austerity isn't about fixing a broken economy at all.

11:56.660 --> 11:57.060
No.

11:57.240 --> 11:58.660
And that's a crucial distinction.

11:59.420 --> 12:09.440
If we connect this to the broader thesis of Flyxion's paper, austerity is framed here as a deliberate technology of class discipline.

12:09.860 --> 12:11.420
A technology of discipline.

12:11.540 --> 12:11.880
Wow.

12:11.880 --> 12:15.640
It is not a necessary belt tightening to balance a spreadsheet.

12:16.140 --> 12:23.980
It is a structural tool designed specifically to eliminate those alternatives that had opened up after the war.

12:24.160 --> 12:27.880
Because if you cut social safety nets through fiscal austerity.

12:28.280 --> 12:31.200
And make money scarce through monetary austerity.

12:31.320 --> 12:34.600
And break union power through industrial austerity.

12:34.680 --> 12:34.960
Mm.

12:35.500 --> 12:39.480
You are forcing people back into a strict state of market dependence.

12:39.480 --> 12:45.000
You have to sell your labor for a wage on the owner's terms.

12:45.320 --> 12:50.540
Because the state has systematically removed any other way for you to survive.

12:51.460 --> 12:53.700
I'm trying to picture this dynamically.

12:54.100 --> 12:55.480
It's like...

12:55.480 --> 13:01.440
Okay, imagine a group of people playing a game of Monopoly.

13:02.020 --> 13:03.040
Okay, Monopoly.

13:03.040 --> 13:07.340
For hours, they've been playing by the rules, paying rent, going bankrupt.

13:08.020 --> 13:12.620
But suddenly, they realize they don't have to play this specific game.

13:12.860 --> 13:15.660
They realize the rules are just printed on cardboard.

13:15.660 --> 13:17.340
The money is just paper.

13:17.800 --> 13:17.820
Right.

13:17.960 --> 13:19.520
The post-war realization.

13:19.800 --> 13:20.160
Exactly.

13:20.740 --> 13:23.640
So they start building their own game in the corner of the room.

13:24.020 --> 13:28.220
They're trading their own resources, maybe sharing the properties, having a great time.

13:28.640 --> 13:33.400
And proving they don't actually need the banker to facilitate their interactions.

13:33.820 --> 13:35.200
And the banker sees this.

13:35.280 --> 13:36.220
Banker sees this.

13:36.220 --> 13:38.700
They just panics at losing their authority.

13:39.220 --> 13:43.040
And instead of trying to convince them to come back, they just walk over to the thermostat,

13:43.340 --> 13:48.860
turn the heat off in the dead of winter, confiscate all the snacks in the house, and lock the front door.

13:49.140 --> 13:51.400
That's a fascinating way to visualize it.

13:51.500 --> 13:55.300
The banker changes the environmental conditions of the room.

13:55.520 --> 13:55.860
Right.

13:56.580 --> 14:00.780
The banker creates a harsh, artificial winter in the house.

14:00.780 --> 14:08.320
And they do it so that the players eventually get so cold and so hungry that they have to come back to the Monopoly board,

14:08.760 --> 14:17.080
sit down, and beg for a few of those colorful $500 bills, just so they can buy a blanket and a sandwich to survive.

14:17.320 --> 14:21.540
It's an incredibly apt analogy for the thesis Matai presents.

14:22.360 --> 14:27.000
The banker isn't confiscating the snacks because the house is genuinely out of food,

14:27.000 --> 14:30.460
or because they need to balance the household budget.

14:30.860 --> 14:32.640
They're doing it to force participation.

14:33.020 --> 14:33.220
Yes.

14:34.820 --> 14:37.920
Austerity, in this view, is the locking of the doors.

14:38.200 --> 14:39.580
It is the artificial winter.

14:39.920 --> 14:42.360
It forces you to rely on the banker's currency.

14:42.980 --> 14:49.800
And this is exactly where Flyxion's paper takes a massive leap from pure history into something completely different.

14:49.860 --> 14:50.400
The physics.

14:50.400 --> 14:50.920
Yes.

14:51.420 --> 14:58.320
Because Flyxion reads Matai's history of this locking of the doors and asks a wild question.

14:59.220 --> 15:04.140
What does this actually look like if we map it using actual theoretical physics?

15:04.320 --> 15:08.980
How do you mathematically represent the confiscation of the snacks and the freezing of the room?

15:09.340 --> 15:09.900
Exactly.

15:10.400 --> 15:13.640
How do you formalize the geometry of class discipline?

15:13.640 --> 15:22.360
If this isn't just an abstract political concept, but a structural reality we live in, we should be able to map its topography.

15:22.860 --> 15:31.940
And this brings us to the first major scientific framework introduced in the text, the Relativistic Scalar Vector Plenum, or RSVP.

15:32.040 --> 15:36.220
Okay, RSVP, Relativistic Scalar Vector Plenum.

15:36.220 --> 15:42.640
Let's take this slow, because I want to make sure you, the listener, can really visualize this alongside me.

15:43.240 --> 15:45.700
First of all, I need to know what a plenum is.

15:46.560 --> 15:51.280
I hear that word, and I think of the space above a drop ceiling in an office building.

15:51.500 --> 15:53.260
That's the HVAC plenum.

15:53.840 --> 15:59.520
In physics, the concept of a plenum is essentially a space that is completely filled with matter or a field.

15:59.900 --> 16:02.280
It is the fundamental opposite of a vacuum.

16:02.500 --> 16:03.880
Okay, so no empty space.

16:03.880 --> 16:07.400
Right. In a vacuum, things can move without interacting with anything else.

16:07.640 --> 16:15.920
In a plenum, every single point in space has properties, and what happens in one area necessarily pushes against and affects the other areas.

16:16.120 --> 16:18.760
It's a continuous, interconnected medium.

16:18.900 --> 16:24.140
So in this model, the social plenum is the entirety of our society and economy.

16:24.640 --> 16:26.540
We're all suspended in it together.

16:27.020 --> 16:27.500
Exactly.

16:27.500 --> 16:34.320
Now, within this RSVP framework, Flyxion introduces three main variables that we need to define.

16:34.940 --> 16:37.980
The first one is represented by the Greek letter phi.

16:38.700 --> 16:39.660
Phi. Okay.

16:40.360 --> 16:41.600
The scalar potential.

16:41.860 --> 16:46.100
If I recall my high school physics, a scalar is just a magnitude, right?

16:46.180 --> 16:46.920
Like temperature.

16:47.140 --> 16:47.740
You've got it.

16:48.280 --> 16:52.360
A scalar field maps a single value to every point in a space.

16:52.360 --> 17:03.620
In this specific model, the scalar potential, FIA, represents the landscape of resource accessibility and decision-making power at any given point in society.

17:04.120 --> 17:05.300
So how should we picture that?

17:05.660 --> 17:10.800
I find it easiest to think of it as a topographic map, like you'd use for hiking.

17:10.800 --> 17:19.940
The high points on this mathematical map, the peaks, represent a massive concentration of wealth, institutional power, and ownership.

17:20.260 --> 17:20.940
And the valleys.

17:21.180 --> 17:25.460
The low points, the valleys, represent extreme scarcity and lack of agency.

17:26.000 --> 17:38.880
Okay, so if you are standing on a high peak of phi, you are a CEO or a major shareholder or a central banker, you have massive access to resources and the power to make decisions that affect the whole map.

17:38.880 --> 17:44.160
And if you are stuck down in a deep valley, you are a gig worker struggling to make rent.

17:44.700 --> 17:46.460
You have very little access to resources.

17:47.140 --> 17:48.100
That makes perfect sense.

17:48.180 --> 17:49.260
That's the topography.

17:49.780 --> 17:51.340
Now what's the second variable?

17:51.740 --> 17:55.040
The second variable interacts directly with that landscape.

17:55.380 --> 17:59.040
It's the vector flow, represented by a lowercase v.

17:59.580 --> 18:04.840
And a vector, unlike a scalar, has both magnitude and direction.

18:05.140 --> 18:05.480
Yes.

18:05.480 --> 18:14.140
In the social planet, this vector flow represents the directed flow of human effort, attention, and economic agency.

18:14.540 --> 18:16.320
It is what people are actually doing.

18:16.400 --> 18:17.660
Like waking up and going to work.

18:17.900 --> 18:24.680
It is you getting up in the morning, commuting to work, producing value, spending money at the grocery store.

18:25.220 --> 18:30.960
It is the literal movement of human energy across that scalar landscape.

18:31.420 --> 18:33.500
Wait, let me make sure I'm connecting these right.

18:33.500 --> 18:41.540
In physics, if you have a topographic landscape, gravity dictates that water will naturally flow down the topography.

18:41.960 --> 18:47.940
Are you saying that in this model, human effort flows according to the shape of the scalar potential landscape?

18:48.060 --> 18:48.660
Precisely.

18:48.960 --> 18:52.440
The shape of the landscape dictates the movement of the people on it.

18:52.900 --> 18:55.160
Energy naturally moves down gradients.

18:55.500 --> 18:55.840
Wow.

18:55.840 --> 18:58.560
Okay, and that brings us to the third variable.

18:59.160 --> 19:01.320
Which adds a crucial layer of complexity.

19:02.220 --> 19:04.740
The entropy field, represented by S.

19:05.160 --> 19:13.200
Now, we have to be careful here because in standard thermodynamics, entropy is often colloquially thought of as just chaos or disorder.

19:13.500 --> 19:14.800
Right, like a messy bedroom.

19:14.800 --> 19:15.600
Exactly.

19:16.080 --> 19:25.140
But in information theory, and in this specific RSVP model, entropy is a measure of the degree of available variation.

19:25.640 --> 19:29.580
It represents the possibility space in a society.

19:29.940 --> 19:32.480
Meaning how many different choices you actually have.

19:32.540 --> 19:32.980
Exactly.

19:33.240 --> 19:37.720
High entropy means there are many viable different ways for a system to exist.

19:37.720 --> 19:46.480
For an individual, it means there are many viable ways to live, to organize, to sustain yourself outside of a single rigid path.

19:46.620 --> 19:47.540
And low entropy.

19:47.940 --> 19:50.680
Low entropy means the system is highly constrained.

19:51.200 --> 19:53.840
There's really only one way things can be arranged.

19:54.040 --> 19:56.380
Let me make sure I have this triad locked in my head.

19:56.500 --> 19:59.840
Phi is the landscape of resources, the mountains and valleys.

20:00.180 --> 20:00.400
Yeah.

20:00.400 --> 20:04.080
V is how human effort actually moves across that landscape.

20:04.080 --> 20:08.860
And S is how many different choices or paths you actually have while you are moving.

20:09.240 --> 20:10.580
That is a perfect summary.

20:11.020 --> 20:21.460
So the big question is, how does Flyxian take Maddy's historical concept of market dependence and map it onto these three physics variables?

20:22.180 --> 20:25.780
This is where the synthesis becomes incredibly elegant.

20:26.700 --> 20:33.340
Maddy argues that the capital order rests entirely on private ownership and the enforcement of market dependence.

20:33.340 --> 20:44.200
In the RSVP model, private ownership is represented as a massive concentration of the scalar potential, phi, at the very top peaks.

20:44.340 --> 20:47.160
Okay, but you said austerity doesn't really operate on the peaks.

20:47.420 --> 20:47.740
Right.

20:47.980 --> 20:50.460
Austerity operates on the bottom of the landscape.

20:51.280 --> 20:55.920
Austerity artificially lowers what the paper calls the subsistence potential.

20:56.100 --> 20:57.600
It drops the floor of phi.

20:57.800 --> 20:59.160
Hold on, let me visualize that.

20:59.440 --> 20:59.600
Yeah.

20:59.600 --> 21:09.460
So when a government enacts fiscal austerity slashing welfare programs, cutting public health care, defunding social housing, they aren't just saving money.

21:10.520 --> 21:16.200
Mathematically, in this space, they are violently dropping the floor of the landscape out from under millions of people.

21:16.400 --> 21:16.740
Yes.

21:17.100 --> 21:22.380
They're creating a precipitous drop, an artificially steep gradient in the landscape.

21:22.380 --> 21:29.280
And remember how we established that human effort, the vector flow V, must flow down gradients.

21:29.620 --> 21:43.320
Because fiscal austerity creates this massive steep drop-off, it forcefully channels all human effort toward one highly specific attractor at the bottom, wage labor.

21:43.660 --> 21:46.620
You can't just live off the land anymore because of enclosure.

21:46.620 --> 21:51.820
And you can't rely on a robust social safety net because of fiscal cuts.

21:52.180 --> 22:03.740
So your energy is violently and predictably pulled toward the only available source of survival, which is selling your labor to the people who control the high points of phi.

22:03.900 --> 22:05.860
That's exactly the geometry of it.

22:05.920 --> 22:10.220
Okay, I think I'm really starting to see the geometry here, but I need to play with the metaphor a bit.

22:10.220 --> 22:16.080
Are we talking about something like a literal gravity, well, actually no, let's go back to an arcade.

22:16.680 --> 22:32.100
If I picture the economy as a pinball machine, is fiscal austerity, basically walking up to the machine and jacking up the back legs so the table is tilted at a brutal, incredibly steep angle.

22:32.200 --> 22:33.260
I love that analogy.

22:33.440 --> 22:37.600
Yes, jacking up the back legs is exactly what dropping the subsistence floor does.

22:37.600 --> 22:40.560
It increases the tilt of the entire social field.

22:40.560 --> 22:45.960
So if the table is tilted that steeply, it almost doesn't matter how you hit the ball.

22:46.880 --> 23:00.420
The ball, which in this case is our human effort, our daily labor, the vector flow V, is going to roll incredibly fast and inevitably right down the middle, straight toward the flippers.

23:00.740 --> 23:03.080
And the flippers are controlled by the employers.

23:03.080 --> 23:10.440
Right. You have absolutely no time to bounce around the bumpers or hang out in the upper corners exploring the top of the board.

23:11.040 --> 23:15.220
The gravity of the tilted table just rips you down to wage labor instantly.

23:15.640 --> 23:21.940
And that tilt is reinforced and accelerated by the other elements of the austerity trinity we discussed.

23:22.720 --> 23:29.040
Remember, monetary austerity, the central banks raising interest rates and contracting the money supply.

23:29.360 --> 23:30.340
How does that fit in?

23:30.340 --> 23:39.200
In the RSVP model, this intervention increases what is called the dissipative coefficient, which is represented by the Greek letter new.

23:39.600 --> 23:45.040
Dissipative coefficient. My brain immediately translates that to friction. Am I off base there?

23:45.080 --> 23:47.320
You are exactly on base. It is friction.

23:47.700 --> 23:53.780
Monetary austerity adds massive systemic friction to the daily lives of workers and small businesses.

23:54.080 --> 23:55.540
Because things cost more.

23:55.540 --> 24:00.760
Yes. When interest rates spike, your credit card debt gets much more expensive to carry.

24:01.160 --> 24:04.480
Your mortgage rates go up, making housing precarious.

24:04.700 --> 24:07.220
Your car alone is harder to pay off.

24:07.280 --> 24:12.400
Your effort, your vector flow dissipates rapidly, just trying to stand still.

24:12.540 --> 24:14.100
You lose energy to the system.

24:14.400 --> 24:20.380
Meanwhile, the major creditors, the people who actually own the debt at the top of the FI landscape,

24:20.380 --> 24:25.000
are completely insulated from this friction. In fact, they profit from it.

24:25.000 --> 24:33.980
And what about the third pillar? Industrial austerity, crushing the unions, lowering wages, removing worker protections.

24:34.360 --> 24:36.660
How does that fit into the pinball machine?

24:36.660 --> 24:43.080
The paper models industrial austerity as restricting the boundary conditions on collective agency.

24:43.460 --> 24:46.380
It prevents the vector flows from aggregating.

24:47.040 --> 24:53.820
So in the pinball analogy, it essentially puts up harsh walls or removes certain bumpers on the machine

24:53.820 --> 24:57.240
so the balls can't group together or get stuck in a safe zone.

24:57.320 --> 24:59.340
Exactly. They isolate the flows.

24:59.340 --> 25:06.740
So you are physically isolating the vector flow, adding exhausting friction to its movement through debt,

25:07.000 --> 25:15.800
and tilting the entire landscape so fiercely that arriving at wage labor is the only mathematically viable destination.

25:16.480 --> 25:18.320
It's engineered inevitability.

25:18.500 --> 25:21.320
Engineered inevitability is the perfect phrase.

25:21.880 --> 25:26.020
But wait, if we look back at the history, the post-WWI era,

25:26.520 --> 25:29.300
people were exploring other destinations, right?

25:29.700 --> 25:35.580
The worker councils in Italy and Britain, they were hanging around the top of the pinball machine.

25:35.880 --> 25:36.080
They were.

25:36.360 --> 25:37.940
How did they manage that?

25:38.100 --> 25:42.840
And how does the model explain the disappearance of those alternatives?

25:43.320 --> 25:47.100
I think this brings us back to that third variable, the entropy field,

25:47.560 --> 25:49.680
and what I want to call the illusion of choice.

25:50.240 --> 25:53.760
This is perhaps the most profound theoretical shift in the paper,

25:54.300 --> 25:57.860
how affliction redefines entropy for political economy.

25:57.860 --> 26:05.920
As we touched on, in this model, high entropy means a high effective dimensionality of the social possibility space.

26:06.540 --> 26:12.720
Let's unpack that phrase, high effective dimensionality, meaning the space isn't just a flat line.

26:12.900 --> 26:14.700
There are multiple directions you can move.

26:15.220 --> 26:18.720
There are many viable states the system can exist in simultaneously.

26:18.720 --> 26:19.920
Exactly.

26:20.700 --> 26:27.780
The post-WWI era, with its worker councils, cooperative logistics, and state-managed production,

26:28.000 --> 26:30.500
was a period of extremely high entropy.

26:30.500 --> 26:35.740
The numbing story of capitalist inevitability had temporarily broken down.

26:36.240 --> 26:42.540
People were actively populating regions of the social plenum that were previously considered utterly inaccessible.

26:42.680 --> 26:45.200
The dimensionality of society expanded.

26:45.940 --> 26:50.700
There were suddenly many valid ways to organize production and sustain life.

26:50.700 --> 26:55.860
So, if high entropy means lots of choices and viable alternatives,

26:55.860 --> 26:59.360
then the technocrats who wanted to restore the capital order,

26:59.840 --> 27:02.540
the ones who wanted to lock everyone back into wage labor,

27:03.080 --> 27:05.120
they couldn't just attack the workers directly.

27:05.460 --> 27:07.860
They had to attack the entropy field itself.

27:08.380 --> 27:09.020
Precisely.

27:09.340 --> 27:14.760
The author argues that austerity is fundamentally an entropic dampener.

27:14.940 --> 27:16.480
An entropic dampener.

27:16.480 --> 27:22.060
The overarching goal of the technocrats that Methe documents was to collapse that expanded,

27:22.260 --> 27:27.520
multidimensional possibility space back into a singular, low-entropy configuration.

27:28.160 --> 27:31.400
They needed to reduce the system down to one viable state,

27:31.840 --> 27:33.600
wage labor under private ownership.

27:33.600 --> 27:39.340
But how do you actually do that in a society that nominally calls itself a democracy?

27:40.060 --> 27:42.200
If you just come out on a podium and say,

27:42.200 --> 27:48.100
hey, everyone, we are actively eliminating your choices and forcing you to work for the factory owners,

27:48.900 --> 27:49.900
people will riot.

27:50.200 --> 27:51.100
We've seen it happen.

27:51.220 --> 27:51.900
Oh, absolutely.

27:52.260 --> 27:55.760
How do you dampen entropy without it looking like naked tyranny?

27:56.040 --> 28:02.200
They do it through the creation and deployment of the ideology of pure economics.

28:03.080 --> 28:03.840
Pure economics.

28:04.120 --> 28:04.380
Yes.

28:04.380 --> 28:11.140
They systematically insulate economic decision-making from democratic participation.

28:11.900 --> 28:13.280
They create central banks.

28:13.480 --> 28:16.040
They establish international credit bodies.

28:16.480 --> 28:19.520
They staff them with credentialed, unelected experts.

28:20.060 --> 28:25.180
And they claim that the policies these bodies enact are just neutral, objective science.

28:25.420 --> 28:25.800
Oh, I see.

28:26.200 --> 28:32.020
In RSVP terms, they use the language of pure economics as a representational technology.

28:32.020 --> 28:36.860
They frame the wage labor configuration not as a brutal political choice,

28:37.000 --> 28:40.740
but as the unique natural equilibrium of the system.

28:41.000 --> 28:43.180
So they walk up to the pinball machine.

28:43.540 --> 28:47.160
They crank the back legs up to a 45-degree angle.

28:47.580 --> 28:52.760
And then when the players complain that the ball is plummeting straight down into the gutter,

28:53.300 --> 28:55.260
the technocrats point at the board and say,

28:55.900 --> 28:57.720
look, it's just gravity.

28:57.840 --> 28:58.420
It's nature.

28:58.560 --> 28:59.800
It's the law of physics.

28:59.800 --> 29:03.940
We'd love to help you, but there's nothing we can do to fight gravity.

29:04.240 --> 29:05.800
That's a brilliant way to frame it.

29:06.540 --> 29:10.300
They naturalize the political stabilization of the field.

29:10.960 --> 29:17.420
Formally, the paper states that this operation reduces the entropy gradient available to the

29:17.420 --> 29:23.860
working class regions and drastically increases the curvature around the wage labor attractor.

29:23.920 --> 29:26.420
Meaning it's physically harder to escape.

29:26.420 --> 29:31.800
They engineer the space so that making local departures from wage labor,

29:32.180 --> 29:35.640
trying to start a cooperative, or attempting to live off the grid,

29:35.820 --> 29:39.280
becomes energetically costly and globally unstable.

29:39.580 --> 29:43.540
I want to pause here and talk about unemployment in the context of this model.

29:43.700 --> 29:43.880
Yeah.

29:43.980 --> 29:47.440
Because this specific section of the paper completely blew my mind.

29:47.440 --> 29:55.900
Usually, we are told by politicians and economists that unemployment is a tragic side effect of a struggling economy.

29:56.080 --> 29:56.920
A bug in the system.

29:57.240 --> 29:57.660
Exactly.

29:57.860 --> 29:59.360
It's a bug we're always trying to fix.

30:00.000 --> 30:03.820
But Flyxion, building directly on Maddy's historical analysis,

30:04.460 --> 30:07.160
says unemployment is not an accident at all.

30:07.400 --> 30:08.740
It is a vital instrument.

30:08.740 --> 30:11.320
Yes, and this is a sobering realization.

30:12.140 --> 30:19.540
In this field theoretic model, unemployment functions as a high gradient region in the scalar potential phi.

30:20.040 --> 30:23.380
It acts as a necessary restoring force.

30:23.680 --> 30:24.420
Like a spring.

30:24.680 --> 30:26.180
Think of a mechanical spring.

30:26.500 --> 30:30.060
If you pull a spring away from its natural resting position,

30:30.560 --> 30:34.220
the restoring force builds up and eventually snaps it back.

30:34.220 --> 30:39.360
When workers are displaced, or when they try to demand higher wages and are fired,

30:39.940 --> 30:46.460
the sheer terror and absolute material deprivation of unemployment acts as that restoring force.

30:46.580 --> 30:50.880
It pushes them, often violently, right back into the wage-labor attractor.

30:51.280 --> 30:55.680
It is the threat of the abyss that keeps the whole system in a low-entropy state.

30:55.880 --> 31:00.180
If you don't accept the terms of wage-labor, you fall into the void.

31:00.180 --> 31:03.980
And for that threat to work, the void has to exist.

31:04.220 --> 31:07.320
And it has to be legitimately terrifying.

31:07.460 --> 31:08.340
It can't be comfortable.

31:08.940 --> 31:13.420
It forces market dependence by making the alternative quite literally lethal,

31:13.640 --> 31:16.440
or at least socially and materially devastating.

31:16.780 --> 31:21.280
I want to take a second and address you, the listener, directly.

31:21.620 --> 31:24.920
Because you might be wondering, why should I care about this math?

31:25.560 --> 31:29.320
Why go through the mental effort of mapping century-old history

31:29.320 --> 31:32.740
onto scalar potentials and entropy gradients?

31:32.740 --> 31:34.260
They can feel very abstract.

31:34.700 --> 31:34.960
Right.

31:35.260 --> 31:38.940
But I will tell you why it resonated so deeply with me when I read it.

31:39.760 --> 31:44.420
Because it completely changes how we view the concept of inevitability.

31:45.620 --> 31:49.540
When you watch the news tomorrow, and a sharply-dressed pundit says,

31:49.540 --> 31:53.520
well, the central bank unfortunately has to raise unemployment to cool inflation.

31:53.520 --> 31:55.100
It's just basic economics.

31:55.100 --> 31:57.980
It can feel so disempowering.

31:58.140 --> 31:59.160
It makes you feel tiny.

31:59.380 --> 31:59.640
Yes.

32:00.280 --> 32:03.020
But this framework suggests the opposite.

32:03.760 --> 32:10.660
It is incredibly liberating to realize that pure economics might just be a representational technology.

32:11.200 --> 32:18.820
It is a language deliberately designed to make a brutal political choice look like an unchangeable law of thermodynamics.

32:18.820 --> 32:20.340
It is not gravity.

32:20.340 --> 32:22.740
It is just a tilted table.

32:23.000 --> 32:24.940
It is a profound paradigm shift.

32:25.780 --> 32:30.440
When you strip away the language of inevitability, you reveal the architecture of power.

32:31.340 --> 32:38.320
But as Flyxion is careful to point out, recognizing that the table is tilted doesn't automatically untilt it.

32:38.760 --> 32:39.060
Right.

32:39.140 --> 32:41.600
Because the system isn't just maintained by ideology.

32:41.920 --> 32:44.060
It's maintained by institutional memory.

32:44.060 --> 32:50.880
Once these political choices are made, they are locked into the system in a very specific, incredibly stubborn way.

32:51.080 --> 32:58.900
And this realization transitions the paper into its second major analytical framework, SpherePop.

32:59.580 --> 32:59.940
Right.

33:00.080 --> 33:04.220
So we've mapped the physics, the RSVP model of how energy flows.

33:04.740 --> 33:09.960
Now the paper shifts gears entirely into computer science and topology.

33:09.960 --> 33:15.160
SpherePop, I'm going to need you to hold my hand on this one.

33:15.540 --> 33:16.760
What exactly is this?

33:16.980 --> 33:24.480
SpherePop is a highly theoretical framework that models computation as an irreversible calculus of events.

33:24.840 --> 33:25.840
Irreversible calculus.

33:26.200 --> 33:26.460
Okay.

33:26.660 --> 33:37.680
To understand why this is useful for understanding society, we have to contrast it with how we usually think about math or classical physics or even daily life where things are often reversible.

33:37.900 --> 33:38.540
Give me an example.

33:38.540 --> 33:43.540
If a ball rolls down a hill, you can apply kinetic force and push it back up the hill.

33:43.940 --> 33:52.800
In basic arithmetic, if you have an equation like 10 plus 5 equals 15, you can simply subtract 5 to get back to your starting point of 10.

33:53.220 --> 33:54.900
There is a fundamental symmetry.

33:55.500 --> 33:56.620
It's the undo button.

33:56.980 --> 34:06.920
If I'm typing a document and I delete a paragraph by mistake, I just hit control Z, the mistake is gone, and the system returns exactly to its previous state.

34:06.920 --> 34:07.640
Exactly.

34:08.020 --> 34:09.780
That is a reversible system.

34:10.340 --> 34:14.180
But SpherePop represents an append-only system.

34:14.240 --> 34:15.300
Append-only.

34:15.440 --> 34:24.820
It models environments where the past is structurally determinative of the present and where time only flows in one direction, leaving permanent scars.

34:24.820 --> 34:33.340
In an append-only system, every time a significant event happens, it is committed to an immutable history.

34:33.800 --> 34:35.140
You cannot overwrite it.

34:35.220 --> 34:36.820
You cannot hit control Z.

34:37.140 --> 34:42.440
And more importantly for our purposes, each new event creates a new topological scope.

34:42.440 --> 34:49.200
What the author calls a bubble that permanently restricts what can be done inside it moving forward.

34:49.520 --> 34:49.720
Okay.

34:49.820 --> 34:51.120
An append-only ledger.

34:51.360 --> 34:54.560
The most common example people might know today is a blockchain.

34:54.840 --> 34:55.020
Right.

34:55.080 --> 34:56.000
It's a great example.

34:56.220 --> 35:00.460
Or, to use a simpler metaphor, a diary written in permanent ink.

35:00.980 --> 35:07.360
You can always turn the page and write something new today, but you can never, ever erase what was written on the pages before.

35:07.360 --> 35:12.340
Every new rule or event is permanently stacked on top of the old rules.

35:12.880 --> 35:15.580
That's a very solid grounding for the concept.

35:15.880 --> 35:23.780
Now, Flyxion argues that this append-only architecture is exactly how austerity operates historically.

35:24.880 --> 35:30.660
Think about the massive, sweeping institutional changes Mate documents in her books.

35:30.780 --> 35:31.760
Like privatizations.

35:31.760 --> 35:45.760
Yes, when a government privatizes a massive public utility like water or rail or energy, or when Italy, under fascism, formally criminalized labor strikes in 1926.

35:46.040 --> 35:51.040
Or when Britain made the disastrous decision to return to the gold standard in 1925.

35:51.260 --> 35:51.660
Exactly.

35:51.840 --> 35:57.980
These were not just minor policy tweaks that the next administration could easily flip back with a quick vote.

35:57.980 --> 36:03.140
Because doing those things changes the fundamental shape of the reality that follows them.

36:03.740 --> 36:07.000
They were what the paper calls scope-defining events.

36:07.340 --> 36:12.720
They completely restructured the very space in which all future politics could happen.

36:13.500 --> 36:17.580
If you privatize the national water supply, you don't just change who gets the bill.

36:18.220 --> 36:22.180
You actively dissolve the institutional knowledge of how to run it publicly.

36:22.500 --> 36:24.980
You rewrite the legal grammar of property rights.

36:24.980 --> 36:27.100
You create a brand new bubble.

36:27.900 --> 36:33.560
And now everyone living inside that bubble has to play by the rules of privatized water.

36:34.280 --> 36:40.840
Even if a new government is elected, they find themselves trapped inside the logic of the previous event.

36:41.060 --> 36:46.060
So the grammar of the bubble is defined by the committed configuration of the past.

36:46.060 --> 36:52.600
And this leads us to one of the most powerful and explanatory concepts in the entire paper.

36:53.560 --> 36:56.400
The structure of nested scopes.

36:56.540 --> 36:57.640
Nested scopes, yes.

36:57.700 --> 37:00.320
When I read this, I pictured those Russian nesting dolls.

37:00.480 --> 37:03.280
You open the big one, there's a smaller one inside, and so on.

37:03.760 --> 37:06.080
Let's try to draw this geometry for the listener.

37:06.860 --> 37:12.940
In our modern economic system, who is sitting in the innermost smallest but most powerful bubble.

37:12.940 --> 37:17.360
The innermost scopes are occupied by the technocratic institutions.

37:17.740 --> 37:18.420
The central banks.

37:18.700 --> 37:30.660
The central banks, like the Federal Reserve or the ECB, the international financial bodies like the IMF or the World Bank, the unelected bodies of credentialed macroeconomic experts.

37:30.660 --> 37:42.520
According to both Maddy's history and Flyxion's topology, modern austerity relies heavily on delegating ultimate economic authority to these specific institutions.

37:42.740 --> 37:51.900
And they sit in the innermost, most consequential bubbles of the sphere pop architecture, largely shielded from public pressure.

37:51.980 --> 37:52.300
Exactly.

37:52.620 --> 37:53.760
And where are we?

37:54.540 --> 37:59.340
Where is the general public, the voters, the people actually experiencing the economy?

37:59.340 --> 38:02.200
We are operating in the outer bubbles.

38:03.100 --> 38:12.740
The vibrant noise of democratic life, the elections, the legislative debates, the social movements, the protests, all of this takes place in the outer scopes.

38:13.060 --> 38:19.260
And crucially, those outer scopes are entirely nested inside the technocratic scope.

38:19.400 --> 38:19.780
Yes.

38:20.000 --> 38:23.060
Wait, I really need to make sure I graph the implications of that.

38:23.060 --> 38:45.900
Are you saying that even if we, the public, vote overwhelmingly for a policy in the outer bubble, let's say we vote for a massive green energy transition or universal health care, if the rules of the inner bubble say inflation must be controlled at all costs and deficit spending is forbidden, the inner rule overrides our vote.

38:45.900 --> 38:46.380
Yes.

38:46.440 --> 38:48.040
And we can't touch that inner rule.

38:48.040 --> 38:53.640
That is the defining structural feature of nested scopes in the sphere pop framework.

38:54.420 --> 39:01.220
In computational logic, the operations of the inner bubble are invisible to and cannot be overwritten by the outer bubbles.

39:01.300 --> 39:01.600
Wow.

39:01.600 --> 39:24.980
The grammar of the inner scope rigorously dictates the boundaries of what is possible in the outer scope, the baseline assumptions that sovereign debt must always be serviced first, that the money supply is a purely technical variable immune to public input, that certain levels of unemployment are natural, that grammar is locked tight in the inner bubble.

39:24.980 --> 39:36.340
This reminds me so intensely of managing software, or playing a video game, the voters, the citizens, we are essentially just the end users of an app.

39:36.640 --> 39:42.580
We are tapping buttons on our screens, swiping left and right, thinking we're making profound choices.

39:42.820 --> 39:46.380
We can choose to engage dark mode or light mode.

39:46.800 --> 39:50.300
We can elect a new avatar, we can rearrange the icons.

39:50.420 --> 39:50.680
Yeah.

39:50.680 --> 39:55.720
But the technocrats in the central banks, they hold the root administrative passwords.

39:56.320 --> 39:59.720
They are modifying the actual base code of the operating system.

40:00.420 --> 40:14.000
We can vote all we want in the user interface, but if the root admin hardcodes a rule at the OS level that says wage labor is mandatory for survival, there is absolutely no button we can click on our screen to change that.

40:14.080 --> 40:15.620
We don't have admin privileges.

40:16.020 --> 40:16.900
That is wild.

40:16.900 --> 40:20.520
It is a deeply resonant way to conceptualize it.

40:20.880 --> 40:32.320
The pervasive ideology of pure economics is essentially the root admins presenting the specific grammar of their code as if it were the immutable structure of reality itself.

40:32.880 --> 40:45.900
They tell the users, look, the app just works this way, it's the laws of physics, when in historical fact, it was deliberately coded that way in 1925 or 1979 and locked into an append-only ledger.

40:45.900 --> 40:49.700
Okay, but this raises a huge mechanical question for me.

40:50.300 --> 41:04.460
If this append-only system is logged in and the root admins are safe in their inner bubble, how exactly does this inner bubble enforce its rules on the rest of the fluid room, the social plenum we talked about in the RSV2 model?

41:04.600 --> 41:06.960
Ah, how the code controls the physics.

41:06.960 --> 41:07.640
Exactly.

41:08.080 --> 41:12.520
How does the computational code actually control the physical flow of human effort?

41:12.940 --> 41:14.420
How do they force us to obey?

41:15.180 --> 41:21.040
And I believe this brings us to the most math-heavy part of the paper, where we have to dive into the math of class rigidity.

41:21.240 --> 41:21.560
Yes.

41:22.320 --> 41:34.440
This is where fliction pulls off a massive intellectual synthesis, bringing the fluid dynamics of the RSVP model and the computational architecture of SpherePOP together into a unified set of equations.

41:34.440 --> 41:40.440
Now, I know we promised not to drown the listener in raw math, so we will keep this highly conceptual.

41:41.180 --> 41:41.600
We will.

41:42.140 --> 41:48.680
But the entire mechanism relies on a foundational principle called the incompressibility condition.

41:48.760 --> 41:49.360
Okay, I'm ready.

41:49.540 --> 41:50.820
Lay the concept on me.

41:51.300 --> 41:55.560
What does it mean for a society to be incompressible?

41:55.560 --> 41:58.500
Let's start with physical fluid dynamics.

41:59.220 --> 42:08.140
If a fluid is incompressible, like water, it means its overall volume is strictly preserved, regardless of the pressure applied to it.

42:08.240 --> 42:11.580
You cannot squeeze a gallon of water into a half-gallon jug.

42:11.860 --> 42:17.500
If you push down on water in one area, it doesn't just disappear or compress into nothing.

42:17.780 --> 42:22.600
It must mathematically expand and displace fluid somewhere else.

42:22.600 --> 42:26.680
Okay, that makes sense physically. How does it apply to the social plenum?

42:27.080 --> 42:35.840
In Flyxion's model, the incompressibility condition encodes the structural rigidity of class relations under the regime of austerity.

42:36.140 --> 42:39.460
It means the economic system is a closed loop.

42:39.700 --> 42:43.580
So it means the economy is essentially a zero-sum game geometrically.

42:43.580 --> 42:46.900
In terms of this specific topography, yes.

42:47.400 --> 42:54.800
Resources, wealth, and agency that flow away from one region of the plenum must mathematically appear in another region.

42:55.560 --> 43:01.320
The gains realized in one sector are structurally, inextricably tied to losses in another.

43:02.140 --> 43:12.040
You cannot just magically generate resource accessibility for the working class without it directly pulling from the massive concentration to fill you at the top.

43:12.040 --> 43:14.740
The system is closed under redistribution.

43:15.240 --> 43:19.280
It resists changes to its overall volume of inequality.

43:19.900 --> 43:24.860
To explain how this closed system actively fights back against attempts to change it,

43:25.500 --> 43:31.740
the paper breaks down that scalar potential, the landscape fee, into three different interacting parts.

43:32.360 --> 43:37.500
And I know the equation looks like a nightmare of Greek letters, but let's take them one by one conceptually.

43:37.700 --> 43:40.080
The first part is the pressure constraint.

43:40.080 --> 43:42.720
Yes, the pressure constraint. What does that do?

43:43.060 --> 43:46.620
The pressure constraints dictate how the system handles local changes.

43:47.000 --> 43:48.160
Let's imagine a scenario.

43:48.840 --> 43:57.180
A local community, maybe a progressive city, decides to implement a strong democratic redistributive policy.

43:58.120 --> 44:03.100
They raise local taxes on corporations to fund robust public housing.

44:03.480 --> 44:09.320
They are attempting to alter the flow of resources locally to raise that subsistence floor.

44:09.320 --> 44:22.140
But because the entire system is incompressible, this local action instantly induces a global system-wide corrective response mediated by the pressure field.

44:22.300 --> 44:32.340
So it's like if workers push down and try to claim space over here, the system instantly reacts somewhere else to balance it out and negate their progress.

44:32.340 --> 44:33.020
Exactly.

44:33.020 --> 44:34.240
Like capital flight.

44:34.560 --> 44:42.300
If a city raises taxes, the corporations just move their headquarters across the border, instantly nullifying the local gain.

44:42.960 --> 44:47.520
Capital flight is a perfect real-world example of this pressure response.

44:48.180 --> 44:51.900
The correction propagates across the entire domain almost instantly.

44:52.440 --> 44:55.080
But crucially, it is not a neutral correction.

44:55.560 --> 44:58.380
The system doesn't just try to find a fair balance.

44:58.380 --> 45:07.180
And this brings us to the most complex but most important term in the decomposition, the non-local boundary contribution.

45:07.660 --> 45:08.140
The boundary.

45:08.740 --> 45:13.420
When I picture the planem as a room filled with fluid, the boundary is the walls of the room, right?

45:13.480 --> 45:15.740
The institutional surface of the capital order.

45:16.140 --> 45:16.520
Correct.

45:17.140 --> 45:18.900
But these walls aren't inert.

45:19.680 --> 45:27.400
This boundary actively generates a signal, which is governed by what the paper calls a boundary memory function.

45:27.400 --> 45:29.040
Boundary memory function.

45:29.080 --> 45:29.320
Yeah.

45:29.560 --> 45:30.720
Do know by Q of T.

45:30.920 --> 45:32.020
Yes, Q of T.

45:32.580 --> 45:39.120
This function continuously aggregates all the past institutional events we talked about in the SpherePop section.

45:39.400 --> 45:46.000
The historical financial regulations, the anti-union labor laws, the massive privatizations.

45:46.740 --> 45:51.340
All those append-only historical events are stored on the boundary of the society.

45:51.340 --> 45:58.460
And they generate a continuous restrictive signal that is injected back into the interior of the system.

45:58.940 --> 46:03.240
So the boundaries of our society aren't just passive containers holding us in.

46:03.620 --> 46:09.380
They are active transmitters, constantly beaming historical instructions back into the room.

46:09.920 --> 46:13.040
They are telling the fluid how it is allowed to move.

46:13.040 --> 46:19.080
What's deeply fascinating here is that this boundary memory depends on the historical momentum of policy.

46:19.780 --> 46:29.100
Past boundary activity decisions made decades ago by central bankers or technocrats is continuously reintroduced into the present dynamics.

46:29.300 --> 46:30.820
Wait, I think this just clicked for me.

46:31.100 --> 46:32.420
This boundary memory function.

46:32.660 --> 46:35.140
Does this explain a paradox that drives me crazy?

46:35.500 --> 46:36.260
Which paradox?

46:36.260 --> 46:43.300
You always hear on the news, after a round of harsh budget cuts or structural adjustment programs in developing nations,

46:43.880 --> 46:46.880
commentators saying austerity failed again.

46:47.300 --> 46:50.060
It didn't create the economic growth it promised.

46:50.980 --> 46:57.160
But despite constantly failing to create growth, the politicians keep prescribing it.

46:57.720 --> 47:00.340
Does this math explain why they keep doing it?

47:00.520 --> 47:00.840
Yes.

47:01.480 --> 47:03.720
It absolutely answers that paradox.

47:03.720 --> 47:13.040
The paper argues that austerity persists even when it demonstrably fails to create economic growth because it is not supposed to create growth.

47:13.360 --> 47:16.520
That is a fundamental misreading of its actual purpose.

47:17.000 --> 47:23.860
Its purpose is to act as a boundary signal designed to maintain the capital order and enforce market dependence.

47:24.560 --> 47:30.900
The failure of its stated public justification, like reducing national debt or spurring innovation,

47:30.900 --> 47:34.520
does not diminish the strength of the boundary signal.

47:34.920 --> 47:36.520
Because the signal is what matters.

47:36.760 --> 47:36.960
Right.

47:37.420 --> 47:42.640
The institutional structures, like central bank independence and international debt obligations,

47:43.360 --> 47:49.140
continue to inject restrictive terms into the landscape regardless of the human or economic outcome.

47:49.600 --> 47:51.960
It is functioning exactly as designed.

47:51.960 --> 47:57.960
Okay, I want to try and translate this intense math back into a physical visual analogy for the listener.

47:58.960 --> 48:03.240
Because the system is incompressible, and because of this boundary signal,

48:03.620 --> 48:07.100
it feels like the economy is a giant waterbed.

48:07.360 --> 48:08.220
A waterbed.

48:08.320 --> 48:09.260
Let's explore that.

48:09.420 --> 48:12.560
The working class is lying on one side of the waterbed,

48:13.060 --> 48:17.100
and capital, the owners, the creditors, are lying on the other.

48:17.100 --> 48:24.880
If the workers organize, push down, and try to claim some space or enact a local policy to gain resources,

48:25.600 --> 48:31.360
the waterbed, being incompressible, instantly forces a bulge on the capital side.

48:31.560 --> 48:33.340
Yes, that's the pressure constraint.

48:33.460 --> 48:36.940
But the boundary memory, those historical institutional rules,

48:37.440 --> 48:43.780
acts like a set of heavy, rigid ratchet straps tightened entirely around the outside of the waterbed

48:43.780 --> 48:45.860
by the technocrats in the inner bubble.

48:45.860 --> 48:47.600
Strapping the whole thing down.

48:47.740 --> 48:47.860
Right.

48:48.260 --> 48:52.680
When the workers push, the straps detect the pressure, tighten automatically,

48:53.040 --> 48:56.740
and force the water to flow right back to the wage-labor attractor.

48:57.280 --> 48:59.640
The system is rigged geometrically.

49:00.420 --> 49:03.800
The boundary continuously speaks into the present landscape,

49:04.340 --> 49:07.140
actively squashing any deviation from the norm.

49:07.580 --> 49:11.140
I think that waterbed analogy captures the mechanics perfectly.

49:11.660 --> 49:13.760
It shows why reform is so difficult.

49:13.760 --> 49:19.760
Class rigidity emerges not just because police physically enforce property laws on the street,

49:19.920 --> 49:24.980
but as a structural mathematical consequence of non-local constraint propagation.

49:25.380 --> 49:29.800
The geometry of the system itself, bound by those historical straps,

49:30.420 --> 49:35.400
violently resists any departure from the low-entropy wage-labor attractor.

49:35.460 --> 49:35.920
Oh, exactly.

49:35.920 --> 49:36.200
Okay.

49:36.640 --> 49:38.580
I'm going to take a deep breath because this is heavy.

49:39.020 --> 49:43.200
We have a tilted pinball machine pulling our energy into wage labor.

49:43.520 --> 49:50.240
We have nested bubbles where we are permanently locked out of the admin privileges of our own society.

49:50.800 --> 49:55.580
We have a strapped-down waterbed that mathematically enforces class discipline

49:55.580 --> 50:00.400
based on 100 years of append-only historical rules that we didn't write.

50:00.500 --> 50:01.100
