And Flyxion concludes this dense paper with a section entirely dedicated to the mechanics of escape.

50:16.660 --> 50:19.020
The paper doesn't just diagnose the problem.

50:19.020 --> 50:25.260
So, if history is an append-only ledger and the geometry is rigged against us,

50:25.440 --> 50:28.820
how do they suggest we actually get out?

50:29.160 --> 50:34.320
This brings us to section 6 of the paper, the mechanics of escape.

50:35.020 --> 50:40.440
And the first thing to understand is a major shift in how we think about social change.

50:40.440 --> 50:48.920
Escape, in this rigorous mathematical model, is not modeled as a single, violent, revolutionary explosion

50:48.920 --> 50:51.880
that magically shatters the system overnight.

50:52.080 --> 50:54.020
Okay, so it's not storing the castle.

50:54.200 --> 50:58.680
It is defined formally as a topological re-democratization.

50:59.480 --> 51:04.020
It requires a deliberate structural expansion of the phase space.

51:04.020 --> 51:09.000
Topological expansion, meaning we don't just try to win the rigged game.

51:09.560 --> 51:12.720
We have to fundamentally change the shape of the rules.

51:13.120 --> 51:15.400
We have to change the geometry of the board.

51:15.680 --> 51:16.080
Exactly.

51:16.300 --> 51:18.460
You can't just push harder on the waterbed.

51:18.560 --> 51:19.560
You have to cut the straps.

51:20.240 --> 51:25.120
The paper outlines three specific mathematical requirements for this escape to occur,

51:25.600 --> 51:30.320
directly mapping Maddy's political interventions onto the field geometry we've discussed.

51:30.320 --> 51:36.160
The first requirement is to make that boundary memory signal democratically responsive.

51:36.660 --> 51:38.160
